## Verdict

**One of the most rigorously specified content-addressed compute cores I have reviewed, and it survives adversarial attack on its core promise.** I went after consensus-safety — any path where two conforming nodes disagree on a `result_hash` — and **found none**: reduction is deterministic leftmost-outermost, redex recognition is by-hash without forcing arguments (R-K/R-S), REF unwraps exactly one level, canonical (de)serialisation is exact on flags+length, and there is no float or iteration-order nondeterminism in Book I. The wave layer is a genuine view — I confirmed Book II cannot fork `eval`.

The findings below are therefore **not** consensus-safety breaks. The one that matters (M1) is a **liveness/fault divergence that makes the reference violate its own MUST-PASS vector TV-7**; the rest is version-anchor / dead-code / documentation drift that erodes the "code = law, version = anchor" discipline without threatening the hash.

